r wove in and out of the trees with ease, constantly on the move. The body structure was feline, a large cat running on two legs, the tail twitching every now and then to avoid a stray branch or clawed thorn. Tanj Dar'Khura continued to thread his way through the dense underbrush, hoping for a clearing up ahead... and solace. He sought to be alone, and alone he was. The spear in his hand had been freshly drenched in blood, and his shield still pulsed magically as he used it to gently clear his path ahead, brushing aside branches.<br>
<br>
He was being chased, though it always seemed that this was the case. And there were claw marks across his thigh, trickles of blood beginning to dry on the cuts in his leggings. The feral tiger he had fought had next to no chance of catching its cousin, a Vah Shir, for Tanj was blessed with the speed of wolves. He could feel the lupine spirit within him, pulsing struggling to be let out. It was this way with them all, they had their own thoughts and wills, but Tanj had to bend them to his own. The relationship with the spirits was an odd one, and one that was different for all shamans.<br>
<br>
He broke free of the trees, and a huge ruined city spread out before him. The newly ordained mystic could feel the spirits out there, ghosts still tied to Norrath, undead. Tanj's pace slowed, the tiger would never be able to find him now, the gap between the two was much too large. He paused to shield his spirit from prying eyes, making himself unseen to the eyes of the living, and moved towards one of the abandoned ruins. A huge set of pillars, cracked and ruined lay out infront of him. Reaching a great height before ending in a cracked top.<br>
<br>
The city must have been great once, home to an empire now destroyed and forgotten with the mists of time. Tanj's eye followed the pillar to its peak, and decided it would do. The cracks in the stone made easy access for climbing, though he was not experienced in such things. As a precaution he once more focused and cast a spell, and his feet slowly lifted off the ground. He levitated for a few moments, just inches of the ground, and then began to climb.<br>
<br>
It was a tough climb, he fell twice on the way to the top, though it might not be called falling. He lost his grip and seperated from the pillar, but his feet remained as if they were on solid ground. Hovering high above the swamp below him. Two steps forward on the unseen surface keeping him from falling and he was able to begin climbing once more. He reached the top, night now fully upon the ruined city.<br>
<br>
With a mere thought he ended the spells that empowered his person. The lupine spirit broke free and coalesced in front of him, into a mist like shape regarding him for an instant before dissapating into nothingness. His feet landed on the pillar top with a soft thud, his reflexes easily absorbing the small shock of standing on solid ground once more. Lastly his image snapped back into view, his form no longer hidden from prying eyes.<br>
<br>
Eyes of gold regarded the sky above, clear, and unclouded. Kunark was a land of no time, an ancient land, and the breathtaking view of the ruins of a once great empire far below were ignored for this instant of clarity. Luclin shown, in all her glory and brought to Tanj memories of home. How long had it been since he had seen his father? Or his mother? He knew they still lived, having had contact with some of his family though he hadn't spoken to his parents in person since his exile. In his mind he pictured his parents, the full moon lending its light to show their features. His father, Sekath, stood before him in mid air. Taller than Tanj and regal in his features, only a few scars marring his light brown coat. His face was showing its age, the fur most likely now giving way to dignified gray. But in his mind Tanj was sure that Sekath was still singing his songs of battle and history, teaching a younger race of bards and story tellers.<br>
<br>
And his mother, Tanj's mother was a shrewd woman, who loved her family fiercely enough to do what she believed best, no matter what the stakes. It was she who helped her son along his path, and it was she who eventually aided him on his last journey from home at a young age. She hid his secrets from his father, though Tanj felt that they both knew and shared all the secrets he had confided in them. At times as a child it felt as if they were acting out their own ballad, and Tanj was the center, it was eerie to see them argue, for his benefit, what was best for him, their only child. He understood their purposes now, he understood why they were the way they were. And despite his dislike of their choices for his upbringing he loved them all the same.<br>
<br>
Watching the stars, Tanj dropped his spear on the column top, and extended each arm, opening his palms and feeling his claws unsheathe themselves from their hiding place in his paws. A feral growl began in his throat slowly growing, he'd been holding it in for much to long and it quickly grew in volume until the roar echoed through the skies, a haunting feral roar of rage, confusion, power and memory. It slowly finished and his arms dropped back to his side, he slowly slumped into a sitting position. All the feelings he couldn't sort out now quiet for a short time, the roar frightening them back to their hiding places in his mind.<br>
<br>
He reached into his pack and removed a potion. A relic of a trial long since past. Another shaman had given it to him, an old mystic. Though Tanj now suspected perhaps it was a spirit. The more powerful he became the more Tanj realized that many of the beings that walked Norrath and Luclin weren't actually of natural origin. Many were just spirits, there for a purpose, or just trapped. But this was something that did not concern him for now.<br>
<br>
Less than a few days ago he was high up in the trees of the Faydark. Among the wood elves of Kelethin. Sitting by himself in an inn's common room he quietly ate regarding those around him. His goals were his own and as usual he never spoke unless spoken to. Tanj's race was imposing compared to the elves,  most of them did not pass his chest in height, and he had to stoop to get inside most doors. As was usually the case, he was simply passing through the area, having no intention on staying long. But something was amiss. He was being watched and he could feel it.<br>
<br>
It had been with him since he entered the city an odd feeling that he was being followed. And with the appearance of a barmaid serving him his food the feeling swelled. She was young for an elf, barely older than a child. Her smile didn't pierce Tanj's heart, he had loved no one besides his parents in his life. He had no room for love, he was a servant, and perhaps if he could find someone who understood his purpose, then he might find love. But for now, he was alone, and besides a few aquantinces he had no true friends. She seemed very intrigued with him, and as she finished serving him she simply said as if in greeting.<br>
<br>
&quot;I've been following you. Vah Shir aren't a common sight here.&quot;<br>
<br>
Tanj's golden eyes blinked, the statement was a surprise to him.<br>
<br>
&quot;Then my feelings of being followed were not unfounded.&quot;<br>
<br>
Her smile faded a bit as she realized he had somehow known of her tracking of him.<br>
<br>
&quot;No they were not. I've never seen your race before, and I'd love a chance to talk to you.&quot;<br>
<br>
Tanj blinked again, no one had ever expressed an interest in him before. People usually spoke to him for two reasons, to ask for his help, or to ask for the blessings from the spirits. Both of which he gave freely, but no one had asked to just speak to him before. He thought it over for a bit as the young elf maiden stood there.<br>
<br>
&quot;Then sit and let us talk.&quot;<br>
<br>
She shook her head and smiled, and turned on her heel and walked over to the barkeep. She spoke for a few moments then returned and took a seat. Perhaps securing a break from work to speak with the strange traveler sitting alone at his table. Tanj's form towered over her, but she showed no sign of fear.<br>
<br>
&quot;What do you wish to know of me?&quot;<br>
<br>
Her green eyes sparkled. It was the first time Tanj had noticed them, they were emerald green. She seemed entirely intrigued with him, not at all romantically, and Tanj felt the same way, she was a puzzle to him.<br>
<br>
&quot;I wish to know who you are. Who are you?&quot;<br>
<br>
The question was the third to catch him off guard tonight, he was beginning to dislike this new feeling of not knowing what was coming next. He hadn't been caught off his guard in some time, it made him feel vulnerable. He answered the question in some manner that satisfied her question and they spoke more through the night. Tanj left the next morning, and that was the end of that quick aquantince. But the question remained.<br>
<br>
&quot;Who are you?&quot;<br>
<br>
<br>
The only response he could find in his heart was this.<br>
<br>
&quot;Who am I? I am no one. I am a tool to be used by the spirits, a balancing force that will do what MUST be done. Whether it is good or evil is not for me to decide.&quot;<br>
<br>
The answer was not in fact a good one. It left him nothing, but it was the truth as far as he was concerned. And the truth ate at him, slowly devouring his thoughts until it was all he could think about. The soul searching had uncovered several things that Tanj felt needed to be dealt with. The small corked bottle in his hand should do just that. The mystic that had given it to him as a gift had also given the following statement.<br>
<br>
&quot;This is for when you seek answers, you will know when, and you will feel the need. Within this liquid are the answers you seek and the direction to guide you. When duty becomes to much to bear and serving your purpose with all your heart is no longer enough, that is the time. Keep it with you at all times, for it will overtake you at the most innapropriate time.&quot;<br>
<br>
The words had struck him as odd, as well as the way which they were formed. He made sense of some of it now, but the rest was still confusing. Well he sought answers, and the answers he sought were buried deep within him. He had been on a journey all his life, but through the phsyical world. Now it was time to see who he was, to find himself. Tanj uncorked the bottle, and sent off a prayer to the spirits for guidance. He downed the contents, and began to fall.<br>
<br>
It was the beginning of something new, and Tanj would find himself and never be the same again. For good or bad the journey he began would change him forever....<br>
<br>
To Be Continued<br>
