<br>
He felt as if he was falling, wind pulling softly at his clothes as he fell into darkness. Echoes of the night all around him, but there was nothing out there. He couldn’t feel anything, not even the familiar touch of the spirits that were present to let him know he was alive. That was his gift, even as a child he was in tune with the spirits, creatures that were once of this world and no were not. Tanj blinked once, and the darkness drifted away, giving way to the flickering light of a torch in his hands. He was small, a kitten, a child. Two companions he played with as a youngling were at his side, ever ready to lead and follow into trouble. They were playful and troublesome children, the kind that made an elder spout off about how things were different in their time.<br>
<br>
Before the threesome was an old and cracked wall, a hole in it just large enough for them to squeeze through with a held breath. They were underneath one of the many uninhabited homes in Shar Vhal, long before Tanj had to learn about Norrath and worlds outside of the Vah Shir city. They slinked through the hole, the crumbling wall around them showing just how old the structure was. The darkness on the other side fled before the torch light, leaving an old and dusty room. Books were strewn about on the floor, “borrowed” from those who no longer read them or appreciated the stories within. This was their retreat, where they hid and read of heroes long dead.<br>
<br>
“Sekath still treats you like a kit Tanj, did you see how he snorted at the idea of you going hunting with me and dad?”<br>
<br>
Jaern giggled as he finished the statement, his father was a well respected hunter of the many species of Hoppers that lived just outside the skirts of town. He was two years senior to Tanj.<br>
<br>
“He treats me like a kit because I hang out with you and Daken. He thinks you are a bad influence on me.”<br>
<br>
“Are we?”<br>
<br>
Daken watched the two quietly, he didn’t like to talk much, and was more of the quiet type. He was thoughtful and noticed many things Tanj and Jaern missed at first glance. His question was a surprise. Tanj shrugged, wondering if Daken had taken offense.<br>
<br>
“I don’t think so besides what’s the worst trouble we’ve been into? Borrowing these books is probably the worst thing we’ve ever done.”<br>
<br>
Daken nodded, though it was in fact he that had done most of the borrowing. His fingers were quick and light, and he was well trained in such things as Thievery. He was an orphan, and a stable boy. One of the royal guards had taken him in and had noticed his aptitude for sneaking about, despite what many of the others thought he encouraged Daken to practice his roguish skills, knowing that they may prove useful to the boy some day. Tanj respected Daken the most out of all those his age, he tried to model himself after him. The young thief was level headed and calm, and did not let his emotions show easily.<br>
<br>
“What do we read about tonight?”<br>
<br>
This was the beginning of a small ritual. Something they had done for some time now. In their hiding place they would read and dream of their futures as heroes like those in the legends. Jaern’s question left silence in its wake for a few short moments. Tanj responded.<br>
<br>
“The birth of the Combine.”<br>
<br>
Daken nodded and mentioned quietly.<br>
<br>
“Never grow tired of history?”<br>
<br>
Tanj shook his head, it was true he never tired of the past, learning what had come before. The question was strange to him though, Daken’s meaning was not clear. His striped face showed that he wouldn’t elaborate on the question. Jaern began to dig amongst the books, brushing dust of a few that hadn’t been touched in a long while until he found what he was looking for. He sat down and Tanj placed the torch in a niche in the wall. Leaving the light to play out over the dirt walled room around them. Jaern cleared his throat and began.<br>
<br>
“The Beginnings.”<br>
<br>
For the next few hours they all read, taking turns, and breaks. They talked about life and history and the stories. Tanj talked about his father and mother, and his uncertainty about his future as a bard. Daken of his adopted father, and life as a stable hand at the castle. Jaern spoke mostly of his father, his hero. They finished another chapter of the book and closed it, done for now. It was far past their curfew, and they knew it. They were more than willing to risk the punishment of staying out late, but only to a certain extent.<br>
<br>
“Well my boys… until next time.”<br>
<br>
Jaern flashed a charismatic smile and exited, leaving Tanj and Daken alone. Daken was standing near the crack in the wall, the fire catching his intense slate grey eyes.<br>
<br>
“Tanj are you all right? The story look like it touched you more than usual.”<br>
<br>
Tanj had lifted the torch from the niche and shrugged at Daken.<br>
<br>
“Just the usual feelings, I don’t know my place… I don’t feel like I fit in.”<br>
<br>
Daken nodded, for some reason he seemed to have learned a lot from being an orphan and from spending time at the palace.<br>
<br>
“We all have a place Tanj. If there is any truth to the histories the ancestors will guide you to your place. Until next time.”<br>
<br>
With that simple farewell Daken slinked into the darkness with the silence of a shadow. Tanj stood in the room alone, looking at the pile of books in disarray. Then he left too. He slinked through the crack then up the stairs leading to the door of the abandoned building. The torch was blown out and laid on the floor next to the door and Tanj slowly opened it revealing the night. The door creaked open completely leaving a huge shadow and two glowing yellow orbs before Tanj. He yelped and jumped back, falling. The huge form stepped inside, the door swinging behind him without any force touching it. Tanj skittered back as the shadow loomed seemingly filling the room.<br>
<br>
“Get away!”<br>
<br>
A voice came soft.<br>
<br>
“Tanj be quiet. I bring a message.”<br>
<br>
The voice was familiar somehow. It sounded like Sekath, but it was distorted. Tanj’s mind frantically searched for an explanation.<br>
<br>
“Who are you?!”<br>
<br>
“You don’t recognize me?”<br>
<br>
Tanj shook his head still scared of who this stranger was. Even with the night vision inherent to his race he couldn’t make out more than the basic features of the large feline before him.<br>
<br>
“Well that doesn’t matter now. Get on your feet.”<br>
<br>
Tanj slowly stood.<br>
<br>
“Your father knows you are here, and he knows what you and your friends do every night. Tomorrow you are to come meet with me, here are your summons. You would do well to be on time.”<br>
<br>
A large calloused paw reached out bearing a small slab of acrylia, markings on it detailing it was a summons that would allow him into the castle on official business. Tanj took it with fumbling hands very scared now as to what was going on. Children were NEVER summoned to the castle, but for acceptance as citizens and to be punished.<br>
<br>
“Remember, tomorrow.”<br>
<br>
With that the huge image smiled, white teeth showing in a predatory grin. The door swung open once more and a farewell was offered that Tanj did not catch completely, just the end of it.<br>
<br>
“….. watch over you.”<br>
<br>
He returned home, feeling hot and uncomfortable. His father was not home, and even if he was Tanj wasn’t sure if he would confront him with what had happened. His mother was asleep, and Tanj was grateful. She would likely have just sighed at his late return and smile knowingly, perhaps she even approved, but it always brought a feeling of guilt. Dinner as a family was always important to Sekath, and lately Tanj had been skirting the affair. He did not sleep well that night, fears for what the new day would bring plagued his dreams.<br>
<br>
Tanj awoke to the smell of breakfast, and his mother waiting for him. He ate in silence, his father still no where to be found, dread still filling in his stomach. Tanj wished his mother good bye and left, heading to the castle with reluctance. He showed his summons to the guards and was lead to a room deep within the bowels of the castle. The large door swung open and the guard motioned for Tanj to enter. Taking a deep breath the young Vah Shir stepped inside with uncertainty.<br>
<br>
Fear overtook him in an instant. His father was there. Sekath regarded him without a single flicker of expression. The other Vah Shir, the looming shape that had revealed itself to him the night before was there now as well. An old wizened looking panther.<br>
<br>
“Hello son.”<br>
<br>
Tanj blinked and tried not to show his immense fear.<br>
<br>
“Hello father.”<br>
<br>
Sekath nodded and continued.<br>
<br>
“You don’t know why you were brought here do you?”<br>
<br>
Tanj shook his head.<br>
<br>
“Elder Sorent here has foreseen that you are not meant to be a bard.”<br>
<br>
The older Vah Shir smiled.<br>
<br>
“The spirits teach us much, and they point to you as a listener of their wisdom.”<br>
<br>
Sekath didn’t seem very happy about this, or perhaps something was worrying him as well.<br>
<br>
“That would explain your love of history and legend but not of song.”<br>
<br>
The Elder took over where Sekath left off.<br>
<br>
“The spirits of those legends are what teach us and our ancestors are what guide us. You can hear them in your heart Tanj.”<br>
<br>
Tanj was reeling from these words. None of it made sense. He was chosen for what? To listen to the whispers of those who stories were written of? To listen to the dead? It didn’t make any sense.<br>
<br>
“I don’t know what you mean, I’m going to be a bard, like my father.”<br>
<br>
Sekath chuckled in a mocking manner.<br>
<br>
“You and I both know you have no love of song my son. I am going to leave you in the care of Elder Sorent, he will train you. You are of an age where you may leave home now. So the Elder will be your new caretaker. Your mother and I will see you when your training is complete.”<br>
<br>
Sekath stood and walked over to his son, who was now trembling with confusion and fear. He looked down at his only child, and in a rare show of affection hugged him. Tanj gripped his father like he was the only thing that mattered in the world. Sekath let go and carefully removed his sons arms from around his waist.<br>
<br>
“I love you son. And we will see each other when your training is complete.”<br>
<br>
With that Sekath exited to the room. The door closing was an ominous thud that left Tanj alone with the Elder. What would happen next was the biggest question in his mind.<br>
<br>
“Your father expects me to train you. But I know you better than you may suspect. You don’t take kindly to people telling you what to do. That will come in time. I will give you a choice, but it shall be our little secret. You have two paths before you, one of certainty and dullness that I shall make for you to follow. Many have trod along this path, and many have failed and succeeded. If you wish the path to becoming a Dar’Khura through the traditional means is there for you to follow, and it would be my honor to guide you.”<br>
<br>
The pause was abrupt and it left silence hanging in the air. Tanj swallowed the bile he felt in his throat. The feeling of abandon that his father had left him with was no comfort and he felt very very much alone at this moment. The silence hung in the air for a few more moments before the elder continued.<br>
<br>
“The second option is a new path. One which has never been trod before by anyone, one that you will be forced make for your own. It is unknown and new, to be forged by your own choices and by your own paws. You will either stay here with me and learn what others have been taught, or you will journey to Norrath and learn what you may discover for yourself, by yourself.”<br>
<br>
“Norrath?!”<br>
<br>
The word escaped him before he could quiet it. Tanj felt like he might pass out. Any Vah Shir who left for the planet below Luclin before gaining his citizenship forsook all ties with the empire. It was exile, self imposed perhaps but exile none the less. The elder watched Tanj closely perhaps knowing the workings of his brain perhaps not.<br>
<br>
“It will mean exile for you, but your spirit is strong. I believe it is the path you should choose.”<br>
<br>
Tanj thought it out in his head, the decision was going to make or break him, and he knew it. But he also knew what his father would want. Sekath was proud of his son, though he didn’t always show it and Tanj knew that his father would rather he try to go where no one had gone before rather than follow the safe path that countless others had. As he tried to quell his feelings of fear and doubt he made his choice.<br>
<br>
“Then I will go to Norrath.”<br>
<br>
Darkness crept into the room and Tanj fell once more into the nothingness around him. His own voice echoed to him from the darkness.<br>
<br>
“Who am I? I am a brave soul.”<br>
