Chapter 3: A Meeting with The Hunter<br>
<br>
A warm hot wind whipped at the short fur that covered Tanj’s face, his eyes were shut, but if they had been open his view would have been the same. Blackness was all about, he wouldn’t even be able to see his own nose should he try, but there was something odd about this part of the journey, the falling continued for what seemed like ages. Tanj slowly opened his eyes to see if he had missed something, he was still in free fall and every direction felt like up. It was disconcerting to his reflexes which constantly tried to position him in the optimal position for landing. The end of a fall would never come though, and as the darkness stretched out for eternity Tanj’s thinking began to clear. The fog of the potion was fading, or so it seemed. Each of his memories had seemed crisp and clear, as if they were the first time he had experienced them, now he had time to think about them and to realize that they had all occurred already. Tanj wondered if his journey was over, if something was wrong with the potion. He stretched his mind out in search of spirits, something familiar he could use to escape the falling. Tanj could find nothing, perhaps something was wrong, and this was the end, or perhaps there was more Tanj could only wait. He blinked and suddenly the darkness gave way.<br>
<br>
Images flew past him, blurry and with ripped edges, as if he were looking at paintings ruined by immersion in water. He recognized himself in some of the images. But he was no longer taking part as he once was. Tanj was now very worried that something was wrong. The shaman tried to call forth a spell to return him to the point where his soul was bound, and it seemed to actually work. A shimmering gate appeared above him and over his shoulder. Without the sound of it opening he would have never known it was there, the images around him now bathing him in various colors of light. He twisted his body and it responded easily in the absence of gravity. The gate stood before him, wind whistling through it violently. Tanj had only one problem, he had no way to pass through it. He flailed his arms but to no use, and his feet had nothing to push on. The gate wouldn’t move towards him either. Tanj growled under his breath angry at his current situation and tried to seek a solution.<br>
<br>
The images continued to swirl about and the gate glowed before him but Tanj could think of no way out of this puzzle. So he tried to cast another spell, this one requiring the call of a spirit. Perhaps with the levitation granted by the hummingbird Tanj could walk across the very air and through the gate. He could feel the spirit out there behind the blurred movie of his life, and he pulled it to him. The spirit flew towards him with great speed, not delaying or arguing with Tanj’s request to aid him, but something was amiss. The spirit slammed into Tanj with a force so powerful he grunted in pain, his ribs shifted with the blow and he was sent flying through the shimmering portal, which closed swiftly behind him.<br>
<br>
Tanj’s eyes were blurred, and it was very difficult to make anything out. Something was certain though, this was most definitely NOT the Plane of Knowledge. His vision slowly cleared and his breathing came back under his control as he began to ignore the pain that was still pulsing in his side. The embers of a large bonfire lay before him, giving the surrounding soft grass an eerie yellow-red glow. Tanj could see short forms stretching out around him, small bumps in the soft grass he now lay on. They were stones, unmarked and smooth. The large Vah Shir rose to his feet and moved a little closer to the fire, wondering what was going on in his mind his thoughts swirled.<br>
<br>
‘What is this nonsense?! I summoned a hummingbird and was greeted with a blow fit for a bull. Where am I now, and why hasn’t the journey ended?!’<br>
<br>
‘Because your Journey has yet to truly begin.’<br>
<br>
Tanj took two steps back in surprise, which placed one foot directly into the hot embers of the now dead bonfire. He yelped as the bottom of his naked foot was seared and hopped back from the fire.<br>
<br>
“Who is that? Who are you spirit?”<br>
<br>
There was no response as Tanj slowly lowered himself into a sitting position to examine the pads of his feet. He thought to himself.<br>
<br>
‘Something is definitely wrong….. There are spirits out there but I don’t recognize any of them.’<br>
<br>
‘Yes Dar’Khura something is VERY wrong. You are not supposed to be here.’<br>
<br>
Tanj growled, and shouted at the silence.<br>
<br>
“THEN WHERE AM I SUPPOSED TO BE?!”<br>
<br>
The sound of wind brushing past the smooth stones embedded in the grass was all the greeted his ears. He was becoming frustrated and angry, his two injuries simply adding to the emotions.<br>
<br>
‘Where AM I supposed to be? I’ve been searching for that answer for sometime… this journey was supposed to help.’<br>
<br>
The voice came once more from all around, and the embers suddenly crackled and rose back into full flame, the sudden infusion of bright light sufficiently blinded Tanj’s low light vision and made him throw up a hand to guard shield his face from the blast of hot air.<br>
<br>
‘You are to be on the path. You’ve lost your way little one!’<br>
<br>
Tanj blinked and slowly lowered his hand, someone was standing in the huge bonfire, a short figure encased in flames. It strode out from the fire, the flames peeling off the silhouette leaving the face and body of a nude male Dark Elf. He grinned showing bright white teeth, which were sharp and pointed like fangs rather than normal teeth. As he continued to walk towards Tanj his body became clothed, or rather encased in darkness. The darkness and shadows that had retreated with the explosion of flame slowly crawled back in as streams of darkness, the climbed up the body of the blue skinned elf as he walked, wrapping about him until he was wearing hoodless robe. He came up to Tanj’s lying form and squatted, regarding Tanj with sharp eyes that were entirely white without pupils. Tanj growled softly at the Dark Elf and backed up a bit shifting himself into a sitting position.<br>
<br>
“Grettings to you my prey, the Dar’Khura, welcome to the Yard. What brings you to my home?”<br>
<br>
‘My PREY?!’<br>
<br>
Tanj’s thoughts were not greeted with a response this time, whoever was hearing them was no longer responding. He tried to form a response, and simply stuttered.<br>
<br>
“I’m… lost.”<br>
<br>
The dark elf nodded.<br>
<br>
“I can see that, it is rare to see my prey here unless I have caught them. Yet you have journeyed here on your own. Do you seek me out for some purpose?”<br>
<br>
Tanj shook his head not wanting anything to do with this frightening image before him. This seemed to amuse the shadow encased Tier’Dal who grinned once more showing a mouth full of fangs.<br>
<br>
“I seek a way back to myself.”<br>
<br>
“I can see that as well, your soul is far from its home Vah Shir. You know not who I am do you?”<br>
<br>
Tanj pondered the question in his head, he had an inkling but he would rather not be right. His eyes wandered to the smooth stones all around, Tanj quietly hoped that this being was not what he appeared to be.<br>
<br>
“You do know don’t you? Or you have some idea? Well you are on the correct path. I am the hunter who has existed as long as the souls have found their homes inside mortal flesh. I am the destroyer of the mortal coils that trap the immortal souls of all, and it is my purpose to hunt. You may call me Death. It is a pleasure to meet you Dar’Khura. I rarely find my prey before I claim their bodies for my trophy. As you may have figured out already the Yard is the eternal trophy room of my hunts, the graves of all those mortal forms I have taken.”<br>
<br>
Death extended its hand towards Tanj, and the shadows peeled back the same way the flames had to reveal a hand. It hung there in the air less than two feet from Tanj’s face. Fear was boiling up in his stomach, but it seemed that Death had no thirst for the “hunt”, as he called it, at this time. Tanj slowly raised a large palm to shake the hand of the Death. They shook and then Death hauled Tanj quickly to his feet. The Vah Shir towered easily over the short elf, and as he peered down Death was surveying the gravestones all about.<br>
<br>
“And you know not why you are here you say. I have not had a visitor in some time, and your hunt has yet to be called, I am not an evil being, so your spirit and body shall survive until the horn is sounded. When that time comes… there are no promises once the hunt is called there is only one conclusion. Lets see if we can get to the bottom of this shall we?”<br>
<br>
Death laughed softly and the wind blew once more making the large bonfire dance in the warm air. Tanj nodded, still very much full of fear but keeping it under control, he responded.<br>
<br>
“I was searching to find myself, and was ripped from that search to this place.”<br>
<br>
Tanj slowly contained his fear and shoved it down as Death seemed to nod, lost in thought still staring at all the stones.<br>
<br>
“You are a shaman, to be truthful your kind visit me the most. Those that understand how to use the spirits, as well as their own can travel places that many know nothing of. I’ve been sought out for the sake of help. I’ve been sought for the sake of power. I’ve even been sought out for the cause of love. But it has never been on accident, those that travel here all do so for some reason. You are the first to not know why he is here.”<br>
<br>
Tanj couldn’t think of a proper response to Death’s ponderings. So he simply described the situation that brought him here.<br>
<br>
“I was experiencing my life as if it was the first time, and then it stopped, I was falling in darkness and sought a way out. I attempted to summon a spirit and instead was forced into this place.”<br>
<br>
Death turned and peered up at Tanj, it seemed like he hadn’t listened to Tanj’s word’s pre-occupied with something else. His eyes slowly crawled down Tanj’s face to his chest, making the Vah Shir’s skin crawl under the fur.<br>
<br>
“No that’s not it at all….. Ah yes, here is the problem.”<br>
<br>
Death reached out a hand and swiftly touched it to Tanj’s chest, a light bright enough to burn away the shadows that made up Death’s clothing emanated from between Tanj’s chest and Death’s palm, the pure white light swirled, then Tanj was shoved back a few feet. He almost stumbled as his feet struggled to keep his body upright. Death held a large white ball in his hand. He peered at it for a few moments, Tanj as well, wondering what that sphere represented. He knew it was not his soul for his soul was what was making up his physical form for the time being, it was something else. Death’s clothing reformed as he peered at the bright white sphere of light, then he plunged two fingers into it. When he removed his other hand there was a long trail of sickly green trailing behind it. It looked like phlegm, a disgusting strand of thick sticky mucus. Death shook his hand to clear it of the start of the thread and continued to pull out more, and more and more. Until it appeared that there was no possible way the sphere could hold so much filth. When death finished there was a small pile of yellowish puss on the ground. He peered at the white sphere which somehow appeared to be more pure now than before.<br>
<br>
“That should do it.”<br>
<br>
“What did - ”<br>
<br>
Tanj began to ask but before he could finish death tossed the sphere at Tanj. He stopped mid sentence and reached out to grab it, he caught it in his hands and it immediately dissipated, becoming absorbed into his body. Death nodded approvingly, and Tanj asked once more.<br>
<br>
“What did you do? What was that ball of light?”<br>
<br>
“That light was the embodiment of your emotions and of your ideas, and faith, essentially it is what makes you, you. But there was something wrong with it. There was too much of this in there.”<br>
<br>
Death motioned to the yellowish goo that lay on the ground… it seemed to quiver as it was pointed to, and it made Tanj’s skin crawl.<br>
<br>
“And what is that?”<br>
<br>
“That? It’s your fear….. You have much more than you know Tanj Dar’Khura, more than I have seen in a single being in a long time. You’ve done a very good job at hiding it, and bottling it and storing it in a safe place where it cannot eat at you. But it’s too much for you to bear and it would have escaped and eaten you alive eventually.”<br>
<br>
“Then I thank you for your help Death –”<br>
<br>
Death cut him off before he could finish his statement.<br>
<br>
“I have not helped you much my Prey. I have simply shown you the root of your biggest problem. The only way to keep your soul free of this menace to your mind is to face it. I suggest you prepare yourself.”<br>
<br>
