<br>
The form loomed up oozing and graying, its form began to harden as it stretched upward, the ooze giving way to a broken and scaled surface. Twin holes of sick yellow opened up in the darkness above, two eyes staring down regarding the tall Vah Shir below. A mouth stretched, pulled from the form by unseen hands, a long jaw spiked with sharp fangs. The skin of the beast crackled as it hardened into something deadly. Death crossed his hands and watched, a look of curiosity on his face, perhaps this was new to him as well.<br>
<br>
Tanj quelled the trembling in his hands by clenching them into fists. He felt no presence he could call to his aid as he stared at the eyes above. The head of the beast lowered slowly from its great height, the mouth opening, cracking through the hardened skin stretching as the maw extended open in a rumble of terror. Tanj was frozen, unable to move his instincts telling him to remain still and this beast would pass over him. His armor was his only protection, his spear and shield no where to be found, and it suddenly felt hot, his quick breathing making it harder to inhale with each breath.<br>
<br>
Death blinked as the crackling continued with a loud snap large shafts of new black and grey puss erupted from the carapace of the body and maw, they hardened as well, as Tanj took a few steps back still having no idea how he would get out of this situation. The shafts split into claws, and hardened, four evil looking blades dripping softly onto the grass. Death spoke up as Tanj continued to remain inactive.<br>
<br>
“You will perish unless you fight, CONFRONT IT Tanj!”<br>
<br>
Tanj gulped again, his hands still clenched tightly into his palms, he tried to summon his courage, and found a few shreds still remained. He took a deep breath and as the monstrous form before him reared back to swing at him Tanj roared, a huge rumbling blast of anger, courage, and even a little fear. It echoed out into the silence of the Yard, bouncing off the stones, and magnifying until it was deafening.<br>
<br>
The creature paused for a split second then swung at Tanj, claws outstretched seeking blood. Tanj’s face twisted into a snarl as he leaped clear of the claws, jumping towards the beast one arm flung out in front of him bent at the elbow to shove the beast back his other hand outstretched behind him open palmed claws extended. His right arm made contact with the shell of the creature’s chest, shoving it back, he could feel it crack slightly underneath his weight and power. He brought his left hand forward to strike, and something formed within it, a spear, his open palm reflexively grasped it and thrust forward with all the power he could muster.<br>
<br>
The spear’s head smashed through the shell of Tanj’s Fear with the sound of shattering glass it pierced the ooze underneath, the creature roared and began took a step back. Tanj pressed forward both feet skidding back in the grass tearing it up as he struggled to push forward, the haft of the spear flexed, bending as the tip met resistance underneath the ooze. His muscles relaxed for a second and then he flexed again redoubling his efforts. The haft of the spear sunk in another few inches and the screeching howl of the beast echoed now through the silence, forcing Tanj to close his eyes at the pain it caused him. He could feel the spear bending in his hands, then snapping as it couldn’t drive any deeper in. The howl ended as the spear broke, the creature recovered from the pain and swung again at Tanj.<br>
<br>
His feet took over, reflexes suddenly honed by adrenaline, his feet began to shove him back, to push him out of danger, but it wasn’t fast enough. One large clawed arm wrapped around his body lifting him off the ground. Tanj struggled as the creature squeezed, cracking his ribs. Its eyes glowed now with a menacing purpose as it’s maw opened again, a tongue of mucus behind the rows of blade like teeth. Tanj lifted the broken spear haft his left hand, and yelled through the pain that was blurring his vision.<br>
<br>
“GO TO HELL!”<br>
<br>
The spear flew from his hand and smashed into the beasts forehead, it flinched, then grinned. Something intelligent behind those eyes laughed softly as its mouth began to drool, in anticipation of its meal. Tanj looked down at death as the clawed fingers moved him towards the abyss of Fear’s stomach.<br>
<br>
“Help me!”<br>
<br>
Death shook his head seeming truly sad.<br>
<br>
“I cannot, this is your fight, you must survive it or die by it. If you fail your soul will wander for I will have not laid it to rest….”<br>
<br>
Death continued speaking but Tanj didn’t hear it, the fist opened and he fell down Fear’s gullet. He looked up and through his blurry vision the last bit of light from the bonfire disappeared as the maw closed above him. Tanj began to pant harder, and winced at his pain. He tried to calm himself, to get his breathing under control. He took a deep breath and lost it just as quickly as his fear filled him.<br>
<br>
He felt the ooze surrounding him flowing into him, through his ears, mouth, eyes, and even his very skin. The form around him flexed and shuddered, shrinking as it seeped back into him filling him to the brim. It was more than he could bear, it was all the fear he had stored, ignored, and shoved down for years. Tanj couldn’t handle it and screamed in pain as he curled up tightly clutching his head. He felt himself lower to the ground as the entire creature was absorbed by him, leaving him coated in a vile substance. He rolled on the ground consumed by his fear, murmuring words that meant nothing. Eventually even the coating on his skin was absorbed leaving him back the way he was. The last thing he saw was Death standing over him a sad expression on his face. He reached out and with two fingers closed Tanj’s eyelids.<br>
Tanj felt himself letting go, losing his wish to live, everything was beginning to get fuzzy around the edges.<br>
<br>
‘NO! You are STRONGER than this DAR’KHURA!’<br>
<br>
The voice came from all around once more, Tanj felt something roll him over, and two sharp objects pierce the flesh on his neck. Something coursed through his veins, and the fuzziness was replaced with pain, burning in all his veins. He sat up still blind and coughed violently, his chest heaving with the force. Tanj’s muscles convulsed unbidden, and heavily, so hard he vomited, the very substance his body absorbed earlier once more being rejected. The sickness continued for what seemed like an eternity, until he was dry heaving. His chest burned from the convulsions and he coughed a few more times, raising a hand to wipe his mouth. His eyes opened slowly to an Erudite woman before him, bald with several tattoos around her head, tattoos of eyes.<br>
<br>
Tanj spat once more clearing his mouth, the sickly puddle of ooze next to him not moving, and looking truly dead. He looked up at the woman before him as he remained in the sitting position, he tried to shake his head clear, while acknowledging her presence.<br>
<br>
“Hello Milady…..”<br>
<br>
Her voice was soft as always.<br>
<br>
“Greetings Tanj, it seems I’ve found you when you needed me most.”<br>
<br>
Death looked disappointed for some reason, he stood a ways away across the bonfire from Tanj and the woman. Tanj breathed a sigh of relief, he was in safe hands, or so he hoped. The shaman knew who this apparition was, she was his chosen spirit, that of the Spider, the tattoos were the hint at her true form.<br>
<br>
“Thank you for saving me…”<br>
<br>
She nodded not smiling.<br>
<br>
“This was the first time you have truly needed my aid, you are strong Tanj, stronger than I had thought when I chose you for my own.”<br>
<br>
Tanj nodded still trying to clear his head of the pain. The choosing ceremony had been a taxing one, he had eventually chosen the quiet observant path of the spider. A silent observer overlooked often, but knowing of many things, and possessing of the venom to defend itself and to harm its foes, that was likely the very thing he felt in his veins that had cleansed him of his fear.<br>
<br>
“You’ve learned much on this journey…. It’s time for the final lesson before you return to your physical self. Mathorin wishes to speak with you. Remember, I am watching Tanj, your deeds are my own, and your failings are my own. Be strong and remember the path you follow is your own, but do not be afraid to ask for help along the way.”<br>
<br>
Tanj bowed his head in thanks as the form of the Erudite woman burst into a pile of a thousand large spiders, falling to the ground skittering in all directions across the grass and into the distant darkness of the yard. A voice whispered.<br>
<br>
‘Keep your Soul strong Tanj, I will be watching.’<br>
<br>
She was gone before Tanj could even form the question: “Who is Mathorin?”<br>
<br>
The bonfire crackled loudly throwing sharp shadows as it flared once more. Death turned and stepped into one of the shadows and disappeared from view, the fire burned down and a new form loomed over him. It was a wrinkled barbarian with a face that bore with it the creases of age and wisdom. Tanj recognized the face, but couldn’t remember from where. In a strong deep voice that carried with it power that belied the age of the body it came from the new presence asked.<br>
<br>
“How does this night find you Tanj?”<br>
<br>
Tanj grunted and pulled himself to a more upright position.<br>
<br>
“This night…. It finds me battered.”<br>
<br>
The craggy face split into a toothy grin, the old barbarian laughed, deep and throaty, Tanj was able to get a clearer view of the barbarian now and that familiarity was still there.<br>
<br>
“Did the potion give you the answers you sought?”<br>
<br>
Revelation hit Tanj, this was the shaman that gave him the very potion that had induced these visions. He didn’t respond at first.<br>
<br>
“Or did it leave you with more questions than you started with?”<br>
<br>
Tanj shook his head.<br>
<br>
“I found some answers, but not all of them…”<br>
<br>
The barbarian shrugged.<br>
<br>
“Then it was some use, that was it’s purpose. I’m here to give you the final lesson before the journey is finished.”<br>
<br>
Tanj nodded the final feelings of the sickness seeping from his body. He moved over a foot or two, distancing himself from the pool of sickness that was once his fear embodied. The old oracle nodded approvingly and began.<br>
<br>
<br>
“Do you know what three things make up all sentient beings Tanj? The body, which all know of, and understand how to use, it is the most basic of all possessions of living things. Your body protects you, it has reflexes to defend itself, it feels pain to tell you when something is wrong, and it reacts on its own if need be. But pain, that is the weakness of the body. You can train yourself to overcome this weakness, and power through, but it comes at a cost.”<br>
<br>
He paused for a moment regarding Tanj as if to make sure he was paying attention before continuing.<br>
<br>
“Next is the mind, it is more complex, you think because of your mind, you feel emotions through it and it helps make up who you are. It can change the type of person you are. The mind has its own weakness, sadness. Sadness fills you Tanj, you know it, and you can’t deny it. It keeps you silent when you should speak, it keeps you hidden in the darkness when you should be seeking the light. Sadness magnifies fear, and fear is the ultimate ailment, for fear is the ailment of the soul.”<br>
<br>
Tanj opened his mouth to ask a question but the old barbarian lifted a hand to stay his words.<br>
<br>
“Finally the soul, it is the most powerful of your possessions, and it suffers from the most powerful ailment. Fear plagues the soul, like pain can plague sore muscles or sadness can wreak havoc with the mind. Your fear has consumed you, and if not for the blessing of the Spider Spirit you would have succumbed to it. You know how to defeat pain, that is with pure force of will, you can ignore it and shove it down. Sadness is different you can ignore it but it will eat at you slowly, never enough to cause any serious problems, but enough for it to affect how you act, though you may not notice it. Sadness can be defeated by finding happiness. You can find happiness many ways. You in particular have found it in companionship, in your few friends. But you still possess sadness, so you must find other sources of happiness. Lastly there is your fear, the sickness of your soul that will break you if you do not cure it. Do you know how to defeat fear Tanj?”<br>
<br>
Tanj answered without blinking, giving the obvious answer.<br>
<br>
“With courage.”<br>
<br>
“Yes… with courage, but where does one find courage? If you are consumed by fear can you find courage? How do you become fearless if you have fear? It is a paradox. There is one true cure to fear, one thing that will clear any being of any fear they may face. The one thing that will make you invincible to anything, whether it be fear, pain or sadness is love. Not the love of the flesh, not the love of brotherhood and companionship, the love of the soul. That is to say true love. Again though you are faced with another paradox, a riddle that faces all creatures, to find true love you must not fear, you must lose your fear to find it. In finding it you will be cleansed of your fear. Do you understand?”<br>
<br>
Tanj shook his head it didn’t make much sense to him. Some of the lesson he understood clearly this riddle was nothing more than a jumble of confusion for him, he thought he understood parts but most of it didn’t make sense. The wrinkled oracle smiled broadly and stretched out a powerful hand, laying it on Tanj’s shoulder. He stared deeply into Tanj’s golden eyes.<br>
<br>
“It will come my son, in time. Until then, go forth and strive to be fearless.”<br>
<br>
Tanj nodded and the image around him suddenly went blurry. The colors faded into one another, the yellow and orange of the fire melting into everything else until there was nothing but a warm orange before him. His eyes opened and he was greeted by a rising sun over the ruins of the ancient city deep within Kunark. He pulled up into a sitting position from where he had laid and dreamed. Along the soft wind a voice whispered.<br>
<br>
“You are Tanj Dar’Khura, you are a strong spirit with much to learn.”<br>
<br>
<br>
